The [fur trade](/Fur_trade) is, at its core, a global enterprise, a vast, intricate web woven from the desire for [animal fur](/Animal_fur) and the relentless pursuit of profit. It encompasses the entire lifecycle of pelts, from their initial acquisition—often through violent means—to their eventual sale and transformation into garments or luxury items. Since the [early modern period](/Early_modern_period), when a truly global market for these coveted materials solidified, the furs of [boreal](/Boreal_ecosystem), polar, and cold temperate mammalian animals have consistently commanded the highest value. These were the creatures whose dense, insulating coats offered protection against the very environments that made their pelts so desirable. Historically, this trade wasn't just about commerce; it was a potent catalyst for human expansion. It spurred the intrepid (or perhaps, more accurately, the avaricious) [exploration and colonization](/European_colonization_of_the_Americas) of vast, untamed territories: the frozen expanse of [Siberia](/Siberia), the sprawling wilderness of northern [North America](/North_America), and even the remote, desolate archipelagos of the [South Shetland](/South_Shetland_Islands) and [South Sandwich Islands](/South_Sandwich_Islands). Such was the human drive for fashion and wealth that no corner of the earth, however inhospitable, was beyond reach.

Today, the once-monumental importance of the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) has undeniably diminished, relegated to a shadow of its former glory. Yet, it persists. The modern industry largely relies on pelts sourced from regulated fur farms, where animals are bred specifically for their coats, and from controlled fur-bearer [trapping](/Trapping) operations. However, this continuation has plunged the industry into a deep and often vitriolic controversy. [Animal rights](/Animal_rights) organizations vehemently oppose the [fur trade](/Fur_trade), presenting compelling arguments that highlight the undeniable suffering inflicted upon animals. They document instances of brutal killings and, in some horrific cases, animals being skinned alive. These accusations resonate deeply with a public increasingly aware of animal welfare. Consequently, fur, once an indispensable material for warmth and a paramount symbol of status, has been substantially replaced in many clothing applications by increasingly sophisticated [synthetic](/Synthetic_fiber) imitations. One need only look at the ruffs adorning the hoods of modern [parkas](/Parka) to see how effectively artificial materials have taken over, a testament to both technological advancement and evolving ethical sensibilities. The demand for genuine fur, while not entirely extinguished, certainly no longer dictates the course of empires.

## Continental fur trade

### Russian fur trade

Before the ambitious and often brutal European colonization of the Americas truly reshaped global commerce, Russia stood as a preeminent, indeed, a colossal, supplier of fur pelts to the eager markets of Western Europe and various regions of Asia. The origins of this extensive trade network can be traced back to the [Early Middle Ages](/Early_Middle_Ages) (roughly 500–1000 AD/CE), evolving initially through a series of exchanges at established trading posts strategically located around the vital waterways of the [Baltic](/Baltic_Sea) and [Black](/Black_Sea) seas. From these coastal hubs, furs flowed inland, with the thriving German city of [Leipzig](/Leipzig) emerging as the primary and most significant trading market destination for these precious commodities. It was [Kievan Rus'](/Kievan_Rus%27), the powerful medieval East Slavic state, that served as the foundational and initial supplier, laying the groundwork for what would become a massive Russian fur enterprise.

Initially, Russia's fur exports consisted predominantly of raw, unprocessed furs, primarily the pelts of common yet valuable forest dwellers such as [martens](/Marten), [beavers](/Beaver), [wolves](/Wolf), [foxes](/Fox), [squirrels](/Squirrel), and [hares](/Hare). However, a significant shift in the scale and scope of the trade occurred between the 16th and 18th centuries. This period saw the relentless expansion of Russian settlers into [Siberia](/Siberia), a vast, unforgiving, yet incredibly resource-rich region. Siberia proved to be a veritable treasure trove, teeming with numerous mammal species whose furs were highly prized, including the elusive [Arctic fox](/Arctic_fox), the solitary [lynx](/Lynx), the incredibly valuable [sable](/Sable), the sought-after [sea otter](/Sea_otter), and the stoat, particularly in its white winter coat, known as [ermine](/Stoat). The pursuit of these exceptionally luxurious pelts, especially the prized [sea otter](/Sea_otter) – initially coveted in China and later for the [northern fur seal](/Northern_fur_seal) – became a powerful driving force behind the [Russian Empire's](/Imperial_Russia) eastward expansion. This insatiable demand directly fueled Russia's push into North America, most notably establishing a significant presence in [Alaska](/Alaska). From the 17th century through the latter half of the 19th century, Russia maintained its position as the world's undisputed largest supplier of fur, a testament to the sheer scale of its Siberian resources and imperial ambition. The [fur trade](/Fur_trade) was not merely an economic activity; it was a foundational pillar in the development of [Siberia](/Siberia), the [Russian Far East](/Russian_Far_East), and indeed, the entire [Russian colonization of the Americas](/Russian_colonization_of_the_Americas). Its importance to the regional economy of Siberia is still recognized today, with the image of the sable proudly serving as a regional symbol for [Sverdlovsk Oblast](/Sverdlovsk_Oblast) in the Urals, and for the [Novosibirsk](/Novosibirsk_Oblast), [Tyumen](/Tyumen_Oblast), and [Irkutsk](/Irkutsk_Oblast) [Oblasts](/Oblast) across Siberia. It seems even the animals, in their absence, can still represent a legacy of human conquest.

Meanwhile, the arrival of Europeans in North America, a continent boasting immense, untouched forests and an astonishing abundance of wildlife, particularly the ubiquitous beaver, irrevocably altered the global fur landscape. By the 17th century, North America had rapidly ascended to become a dominant supplier of fur pelts, feeding the burgeoning European markets for fur [felt](/Felt) hats, as well as the ever-growing demand for fur trimmings and garments. In an era long before the widespread distribution of coal for heating, furs were not just a luxury; they were a critical necessity for crafting warm clothing, a matter of survival in the colder European climates. Portugal and Spain, with their extensive maritime networks and early colonial ventures, played significant roles in the fur trading economy following the 15th century, especially through their involvement in the fashionable fur hat industry. The desire for a beaver hat, it seems, was once enough to redraw maps and reshape continents.

#### Siberian fur trade

*Main article: [Siberian fur trade](/Siberian_fur_trade)*

Possessions of the city-state of [Novgorod](/Novgorod_Republic) c. &#8201;1400. Novgorod created a vast territorial empire and controlled much of the fur trade with Europe.

The roots of the Siberian [fur trade](/Fur_trade) stretch back remarkably far, with merchants and influential [boyars](/Boyar) from the powerful city-state of [Novgorod](/Novgorod_Republic) beginning their exploitation of the region's abundant fur resources as early as the 10th century. Their initial inroads were made "beyond the portage," a crucial watershed at the [White Lake](/Lake_Beloye_(disambiguation)) that served as a natural gateway to the entire northwestern expanse of Eurasia. These enterprising Novgorodians systematically established a network of [trading posts](/Trading_post) along the intricate river systems of the [Volga](/Volga_River) and [Vychegda](/Vychegda_River). Their strategy was straightforward and effective: they compelled the indigenous [Komi](/Komi_peoples) people to provide them with furs as a form of [tribute](/Tribute), effectively turning natural resources into a steady stream of wealth. Novgorod itself, ideally positioned, flourished as the easternmost [trading post](/Kontor) of the formidable [Hanseatic League](/Hanseatic_League), a powerful commercial and defensive confederation of merchant guilds and market towns in Northern Central Europe.

As their ambitions grew, Novgorodians pushed even further east and north, inevitably encountering new native populations. They came into contact with the Pechora people residing in the [Pechora River](/Pechora_River) valley and the [Yugra](/Yugra) people, whose territories lay near the imposing [Urals](/Ural_Mountains). These tribes, unlike the Komi, proved to be far more resistant to Russian encroachment, leading to numerous deadly clashes and the killing of many Russian tribute-collectors throughout the tenth and eleventh centuries. The land, it seems, had its own defenders.

As the [Grand Principality of Moscow](/Grand_Principality_of_Moscow) steadily accumulated power and influence over the course of the 15th century, embarking on its ambitious project of "[gathering of the Russian lands](/Gathering_of_the_Russian_lands)," it inevitably began to challenge the Novgorodians' long-standing dominance in the northern Russian [fur trade](/Fur_trade). This rivalry, a clash of emerging imperial ambitions, ultimately saw Novgorod lose its prized autonomy and be fully absorbed by the ascendant authorities in Moscow, along with its vast and fur-rich hinterland. Simultaneously, Moscow adopted a strategy of systematic subjugation against many of the native tribes, a process often facilitated by cunning manipulation. One particularly effective tactic involved exploiting existing antagonisms and rivalries between different tribes, notably the Komi and Yugra, by recruiting warriors from one tribe to fight in Muscovite armies against another. While early campaigns against Siberian native tribes remained somewhat sporadic, they escalated dramatically, beginning on [a much larger scale](/Yugra_campaigns) in 1483 and again in 1499–1500, marking a decisive shift towards more aggressive territorial expansion.

Beyond the existing power of the Novgorodians and the tenacious resistance of the indigenous peoples, the Muscovites also found themselves in direct confrontation with various Muslim [Tatar khanates](/Tatars) to their east. In a pivotal moment in 1552, [Ivan IV](/Ivan_the_Terrible), often known as Ivan the Terrible and then the self-proclaimed [tsar of all Russia](/Tsar_of_all_Russia), took a monumental step towards solidifying Russian hegemony in Siberia. He dispatched a formidable army to attack the [Khanate of Kazan](/Khanate_of_Kazan), a campaign that resulted in the strategic acquisition of a vast territory stretching from the [Volga](/Volga_River) to the [Ural Mountains](/Ural_Mountains). From this point forward, the resonant phrase, "ruler of [Obdor](/Obdoria), [Konda](/Kondia), and all Siberian lands," became an integral part of the official title of the [tsar](/Tsar) in Moscow, underscoring the newly acquired imperial reach.

However, this expansion was far from seamless. Problems quickly arose after 1558 when Ivan IV, in a move to further consolidate control, sent Grigory Stroganov&#160;&#91;ru&#93; ( c. &#8201;1533–1577), a prominent merchant and industrialist, to colonize lands along the [Kama](/Kama_(river)) River and to subjugate and enserf the [Komi](/Komi_peoples) living there. The powerful [Stroganov family](/Stroganov_family) soon found themselves embroiled in a bitter conflict in 1573 with the [khan of Sibir](/Khanate_of_Sibir), whose ancestral lands they were aggressively encroaching upon. Ivan, ever the pragmatist, instructed the Stroganovs to hire [Cossack](/Cossacks) mercenaries, renowned for their martial prowess, to protect the new settlements from the Tatar incursions. From approximately 1581, the fiercely independent band of Cossacks led by the legendary [Yermak Timofeyevich](/Yermak_Timofeyevich) engaged in numerous battles, a period of intense conflict that eventually culminated in a Tatar victory in 1584 and the temporary cessation of Russian occupation in that particular area. Yet, the imperial ambition was not to be deterred. In 1584, Ivan's son [Feodor](/Feodor_I_of_Russia) swiftly dispatched military governors, known as [voivodas](/Voivode), and additional soldiers to reclaim Yermak's hard-won conquests and to officially annex the territory previously held by the [Khanate of Sibir](/Khanate_of_Sibir). Similar skirmishes and territorial disputes with Tartars became a recurring theme across Siberia as Russian expansion continued its relentless march eastward, a testament to the high stakes of this "soft gold" conquest.

Map of Asia in 1636. With the [conquest of Siberia](/Russian_conquest_of_Siberia) in the 16th and 17th centuries, Russia gained access to the world's richest source of high quality fur.

The Russian conquerors, driven by imperial ambition and a clear sense of cultural superiority, treated the indigenous peoples of Siberia as little more than easily exploited subjects, inherently inferior to their own. As they pressed deeper into the vastness of Siberia, traders and officials established a network of outposts or winter lodges, known as *zimovye*&#160;&#91;ru&#93;, which served as both temporary residences and collection points for the fur tribute exacted from the native tribes. By 1620, a mere few decades after the initial incursions, Russia had consolidated its dominance over an astonishing expanse of land, stretching from the formidable Urals eastward to the [Yenisey](/Yenisei_River) valley and extending south to the majestic [Altai Mountains](/Altai_Mountains), encompassing an area of approximately 1.25&#160;million square miles. This rapid territorial acquisition was largely fueled by the insatiable demand for furs.

Indeed, furs would emerge as Russia's single largest source of wealth and hard currency throughout the 16th and 17th centuries. In an era where keeping pace with the technological and military advancements of Western Europe necessitated significant capital, and Russia notably lacked abundant sources of gold and silver, furs became the indispensable commodity. They were aptly dubbed "soft gold," providing Russia with the crucial hard currency needed to navigate the complex international economic landscape. The Russian government, ever keen to extract maximum value, generated substantial income from the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) through a dual taxation system: the [yasak](/Yasak) (or *iasak*) tax, levied directly on native populations, and the 10% "Sovereign Tithing Tax," imposed on both the catch and the subsequent sale of fur pelts.

The demand for furs in Western Europe was nothing short of immense, particularly for the luxurious sable and marten, as European forest resources had been severely depleted through centuries of over-hunting, rendering local furs exceedingly scarce. This imbalance created a lucrative opportunity for Russia. The [fur trade](/Fur_trade) allowed Russia to procure essential goods from Europe that it either lacked or could not produce efficiently, including vital materials such as lead, tin, precious metals, high-quality textiles, firearms, and sulfur. Beyond Europe, Russia also engaged in extensive fur trade with the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire) and various other countries across the Middle East, exchanging its valuable pelts for sought-after commodities like silk, exotic textiles, fragrant spices, and dried fruit. The extraordinarily high prices that sable, black fox, and marten furs could command in these international markets ignited a veritable "fur fever," a gold rush of sorts that prompted countless Russians to venture into Siberia as independent trappers, driven by the lure of immense wealth. From 1585 to 1680, this relentless pursuit yielded tens of thousands of sable and other valuable pelts each year, fundamentally transforming the Siberian landscape and economy.

[Cossacks](/Cossacks) collecting yasak in Siberia

The primary mechanism through which the Russian state systematically acquired furs was by exacting a fur tribute from the indigenous Siberian natives, a tax known as *yasak*. This *yasak* typically mandated a fixed number of sable pelts, which every male tribe member aged at least fifteen years was obligated to supply to Russian officials. Enforcement of this tribute was often brutal, relying heavily on coercion and the practice of taking hostages, usually high-ranking tribal chiefs or members of their families, ensuring compliance through fear. Initially, Russian settlers were content to engage in a seemingly more equitable trade with the natives, exchanging European manufactured goods like metal pots, axes, and glass beads for the prized sables that the indigenous peoples, at the time, did not value in the same way. However, as the demand for furs intensified and the economic stakes grew higher, violence and outright force rapidly supplanted peaceful exchange as the primary means of obtaining these valuable pelts.

A significant systemic flaw within the *yasak* system was the rampant corruption among Russian governors, who, tellingly, received no official salary. This structural deficiency incentivized, if not outright forced, them to resort to illegal means to acquire furs for their personal gain. These illicit activities included bribing customs officials to allow them to personally collect *yasak*, extorting natives by demanding tribute multiple times over, or even requiring tribute from independent trappers who were technically outside the direct tribal structure. It was a system designed to fail, fueled by human nature and imperial neglect.

Russian fur trappers, known as *[promyshlenniki](/Promyshlenniki)*, operated in highly organized bands of 10–15 men, referred to as *vatagi*&#160;&#91;ru&#93;. These *vatagi* generally fell into one of two distinct categories. The first consisted of independent bands, often comprising blood relatives or unrelated individuals, who pooled their resources and contributed an equal share of the hunting-expedition expenses. The second type was composed of hired hunters, whose expeditions were fully funded by the trading companies that employed them.

Members of an independent *vataga* operated as a cohesive unit, cooperatively sharing all the arduous and necessary work associated with fur trapping. This included the meticulous tasks of making and setting traps, constructing temporary forts and camps for shelter, diligently stockpiling essential provisions like firewood and grain, and engaging in fishing to supplement their diet. All the valuable fur pelts acquired during their endeavors were placed into a common pool, which the band then divided equally among themselves, but only after the Russian officials had exacted their mandatory 10% tithing tax.

Conversely, a trading company provided its hired fur-trappers with all the necessary capital for transportation, food, and supplies. Once the hunt was successfully concluded, the employer claimed a substantial two-thirds of the pelts, with the remaining third being sold and the proceeds divided evenly among the hired laborers. During the warmer summer months, *promyshlenniki* would establish temporary summer camps to stockpile grain and fish, and many would engage in agricultural work for additional income, a brief respite from the relentless pursuit of fur. As late summer transitioned into early fall, the *vatagi* would depart their summer grounds, meticulously survey their designated hunting territory, and establish a more robust winter camp. Each member of the group was typically responsible for setting at least 10 traps, and the *vatagi* would often subdivide into smaller, more efficient groups of two to three men who collaborated to maintain specific trap lines. The *promyshlenniki* checked their traps daily, resetting them or replacing bait whenever necessary, a constant vigilance against the elements and the cunning of their prey. They employed both passive hunting strategies, relying on traps, and more active approaches, which involved the skilled use of hunting-dogs and bows-and-arrows. Occasionally, hunters would meticulously follow sable tracks to their burrows, strategically placing nets around the entrances, and patiently waiting for the valuable sable to emerge.

The hunting season was dictated by the harsh Siberian climate, commencing around the time of the first snow in October or November and extending through the early spring. Hunting expeditions were not fleeting ventures; they typically lasted two to three years on average, though some occasionally stretched even longer. Given the extended duration of these hunts and the inherent difficulty and high cost of returning to Russia, many *promyshlenniki*, beginning around the 1650s–1660s, made the pragmatic decision to settle permanently in Siberia, further cementing the Russian presence in the vast territory. Between 1620 and 1680, a staggering total of 15,983 trappers operated in Siberia, each one a testament to the allure and hardship of the "soft gold" trade.

### North American fur trade

*Main article: [North American fur trade](/North_American_fur_trade)*

#### Fur-hat industry

The [North American fur trade](/North_American_fur_trade) was not merely an economic activity; it was a foundational element in the nascent stages of European engagement with the continent, blossoming as early as the 1500s through interactions between Europeans and [First Nations](/First_Nations_in_Canada) peoples. This burgeoning commerce formed a central, often pivotal, part of the early [history of contact](/European_colonization_of_the_Americas) between European colonizers and the native peoples of what would eventually become the [United States](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) and [Canada](/First_Nations_in_Canada). Dr. S. E. Dawson's acclaimed work, "The Saint Lawrence Its Basin & Border-Lands," meticulously details the approximately twenty principal "gateways" that interconnected the mighty [St. Lawrence River](/St._Lawrence_River) with its surrounding basins. These pathways, though all once vital canoe routes, were not universally designated as trade routes, a distinction often lost in simplified historical narratives.

By 1578, the waters around [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_(island)) were already bustling with 350 European fishing vessels, a testament to the early and sustained European presence. It was from these maritime endeavors that a more systematic trade began to emerge: sailors, often as a side venture, initiated exchanges of metal implements—particularly knives, a commodity highly valued by the indigenous peoples for their superior utility—for the natives' well-worn pelts. The initial demand focused primarily on beaver and sea otter, with deer, bear, ermine, and skunk pelts also occasionally entering the market.

Crucially, these fur robes, essentially blankets crafted from sewn-together, native-tanned beaver pelts, known as *castor gras* in French and "coat beaver" in English, soon garnered significant attention from the burgeoning felt-hat making industry. These pelts were recognized as uniquely suitable for the felting process. Some historians, in their quest to decipher the term *castor gras*, have theorized that "coat beaver" was exceptionally rich in human oils from prolonged wear, suggesting this quality enhanced its attractiveness to hatters. However, this seems fundamentally improbable, as grease, by its very nature, tends to interfere with the delicate felting of wool, rather than improving it. By the 1580s, beaver "wool" had firmly established itself as the primary raw material for French felt-hatters, a testament to its superior quality. English hat makers soon followed suit, especially after [Huguenot](/Huguenot) refugees, bringing with them their specialized skills and sophisticated tastes, introduced these techniques and fashions from France. The allure of a well-made hat, it seems, was a powerful, if ultimately destructive, force.

#### Early organization

General map of the "Beaver Hunting Grounds" described in "Deed from the Five Nations to the King, of their Beaver Hunting Ground", also known as the [Nanfan Treaty](/Nanfan_Treaty) of 1701

The nascent [fur trade](/Fur_trade) in [New France](/New_France) saw its first organized attempt at control under Captain Chauvin. In 1599, he shrewdly secured a [monopoly](/Monopoly) from [Henry IV](/Henry_IV_of_France), aiming to establish a colonial outpost near the mouth of the [Saguenay River](/Saguenay_River) at [Tadoussac](/Tadoussac). This marked the beginning of a more structured, albeit often chaotic, engagement. French explorers, such as the iconic [Samuel de Champlain](/Samuel_de_Champlain), along with the intrepid [voyageurs](/Voyageurs) and independent wilderness traders known as [Coureur des bois](/Coureur_des_bois)—figures like [Étienne Brûlé](/%C3%89tienne_Br%C3%BBl%C3%A9), [Radisson](/Pierre-Esprit_Radisson), [La Salle](/Ren%C3%A9-Robert_Cavelier,_Sieur_de_La_Salle), and [Le Sueur](/Pierre-Charles_Le_Sueur)—ventured deep into the continent. While their primary objective was often the discovery of new routes, they simultaneously forged intricate relationships with [Amerindians](/Amerindians), steadily expanding the exchange of valuable fur pelts for items considered 'common' by the Europeans. Mammalian winter pelts were particularly prized for their superior warmth and insulating properties, with animal pelts, especially beaver wool, being transformed into felt hats. These hats, far from mere utilitarian headwear, quickly became an expensive and potent status symbol across Europe. The relentless demand for beaver wool felt hats was so intense that the beaver population in Europe and European Russia had been almost entirely decimated through over-exploitation, creating a desperate need for new sources.

Across the Atlantic, in 1613, Dallas Carite and [Adriaen Block](/Adriaen_Block) spearheaded separate expeditions with the explicit goal of establishing robust fur trade relationships with the powerful [Mohawk](/Mohawk_people) and [Mohican](/Mohican) tribes. By 1614, the [Dutch](/Dutch_people) were dispatching vessels with increasing regularity, eager to secure the substantial economic returns offered by the burgeoning [fur trade](/Fur_trade). The fur trade of New Netherland, facilitated through the bustling port of [New Amsterdam](/New_Amsterdam) (modern-day New York City), relied heavily on the strategic trading depot at [Fort Orange](/Fort_Orange) (present-day Albany) on the upper [Hudson River](/Hudson_River). It is widely believed that a significant portion of this fur actually originated in Canada, illicitly smuggled south by enterprising individuals keen to circumvent the government-imposed monopoly in the French colony.

[Rupert's Land](/Rupert%27s_Land), granted as a commercial monopoly to the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company) in 1670

England, somewhat slower to enter the fiercely competitive American [fur trade](/Fur_trade) than its French and [Dutch Republic](/Dutch_Republic) counterparts, quickly learned the ropes once its colonies were established. Development companies recognized that furs offered the most efficient means for colonists to remit value back to the mother country. Furs were being dispatched from [Virginia](/Virginia) shortly after 1610, and the [Plymouth Colony](/Plymouth_Colony) was sending substantial quantities of beaver pelts to its London agents throughout the 1620s and 1630s, signaling a rapid escalation of English involvement. London merchants, ever opportunistic, even attempted to seize control of France's lucrative [fur trade](/Fur_trade) in the [St Lawrence River](/Saint_Lawrence_River) valley. Capitalizing on one of England's intermittent wars with France, [Sir David Kirke](/Sir_David_Kirke) successfully captured Quebec in 1629, promptly bringing the entire year's produce of furs back to London. Other English merchants also engaged in fur trading around the [Saint Lawrence River](/Saint_Lawrence_River) region in the 1630s, though these efforts were officially discouraged by the Crown. Such direct challenges ceased as France, determined to protect its valuable colonial assets, significantly strengthened its presence in Canada.

Throughout the 17th and 18th centuries, much of the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) in North America was increasingly dominated by the elaborate Canadian fur shipping network that had developed within New France. This network operated under a series of fur monopolies, initially held by the [Company of One Hundred Associates](/Company_of_One_Hundred_Associates), and subsequently, from 1664, by the [French West India Company](/French_West_India_Company). This system steadily expanded its fur trapping and shipping operations across a sprawling network of frontier forts, pushing ever westward. This expansion eventually reached all the way to what is now modern-day [Winnipeg](/Winnipeg) in Western Canada by the mid-1700s, bringing French traders into direct contact and often conflict with English fur trappers operating out of [York Factory](/York_Factory) on [Hudson Bay](/Hudson_Bay). Concurrently, the [New England](/New_England) fur trade also saw significant expansion, not only pushing inland but also extending northward along the coast into the rich [Bay of Fundy](/Bay_of_Fundy) region. London's access to high-quality furs received a substantial boost with the takeover of New Amsterdam, whereupon the lucrative fur trade of that colony (renamed New York) seamlessly transitioned into English hands following the 1667 [Treaty of Breda](/Treaty_of_Breda_(1667)).

Fur traders in Canada, trading with Native Americans, 1777

In 1668, the English [fur trade](/Fur_trade) embarked on a pivotal new phase, largely due to the ingenuity and frustration of two French citizens, [Pierre-Esprit Radisson](/Pierre-Esprit_Radisson) and [Médard des Groseilliers](/M%C3%A9dard_des_Groseilliers). These audacious explorers had achieved remarkable success trading furs west of [Lake Superior](/Lake_Superior) in 1659–60. However, upon their return to Canada, their substantial haul of furs was largely confiscated by the colonial authorities, a clear demonstration of the stifling effects of monopolies. Their extensive trading voyage had convinced them that the richest fur country lay far to the north and west, a region they believed could be most effectively accessed by ships sailing directly into [Hudson Bay](/Hudson_Bay). Given their harsh treatment in Canada, it became clear they would find no support from France for such an ambitious scheme. The pair, undeterred, journeyed to New England, where they managed to secure local financial backing for at least two attempts to reach Hudson Bay, both of which, unfortunately, proved unsuccessful. Yet, their revolutionary ideas had not gone unnoticed. Whispers of their daring plan eventually reached the ears of English authorities, and in 1665, Radisson and Groseilliers were persuaded to travel to [London](/London). After overcoming several initial setbacks, a group of astute English investors was eventually found to back another, more promising attempt to reach Hudson Bay.

Two ships were dispatched in 1668. One, with Radisson aboard, was forced to turn back due to unforeseen circumstances. However, the other, the *[Nonsuch](/Nonsuch_(1650_ship))*, carrying Groseilliers, successfully navigated its way into the bay. There, the crew engaged in fruitful trade with the indigenous peoples, collecting an impressive cargo of fine beaver skins before the expedition triumphantly returned to London in October 1669. The delighted investors, recognizing the immense potential, promptly sought a royal charter, which they obtained the following year. This pivotal charter officially established the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company) and, crucially, granted it an exclusive monopoly to trade into all the rivers that emptied into Hudson Bay, effectively giving them control over a vast and incredibly rich fur-bearing territory. From 1670 onwards, the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company) maintained a consistent schedule, dispatching two or three trading ships into the bay each year. These vessels returned laden with furs, primarily beaver, which were then sold, sometimes through private treaty but more often via public auction. The beaver pelts were predominantly purchased by the English hat-making industry, while the more luxurious fine furs found their way to markets in the [Netherlands](/Netherlands) and [Germany](/Germany), illustrating the diverse European demand.

Meanwhile, in the [Southern colonies](/Southern_Colonies) of North America, a different, yet equally significant, [deerskin trade](/Deerskin_trade) was established around 1670. This trade was centered at the bustling export hub of [Charleston, South Carolina](/Charleston,_South_Carolina). News of the lucrative exchange spread rapidly among Native hunters: Europeans were willing to trade highly desired European-manufactured goods for pelts. Carolinian traders meticulously stocked a wide array of items, including axe heads, knives, awls, fish hooks, various types and colors of cloth, woolen blankets, linen shirts, kettles, jewelry, glass beads, [muskets](/Musket), ammunition, and powder, all to be exchanged on a 'per pelt' basis.

A darker side to this exchange emerged as colonial trading posts in the southern colonies also introduced numerous types of alcohol, particularly brandy and rum, as a commodity for trade. European traders flocked to the North American continent, reaping immense profits from these exchanges. Consider the stark economics: a [metal](/Metal) axe head, for example, could be exchanged for a single beaver pelt, often referred to as a 'beaver blanket.' That very same pelt, when brought back to England, could fetch enough to purchase dozens of [axe](/Axe) heads, making the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) an extraordinarily lucrative venture for the Europeans. The Native Americans, for their part, derived substantial benefits as well, as the readily available [iron](/Iron) axe heads replaced their labor-intensive, hand-made stone axe heads, representing a significant technological upgrade. However, the colonists soon began to witness the devastating effects of alcohol on Native communities, leading to widespread social problems. Tribal chiefs, recognizing the destructive impact, vehemently objected to its sale and trade. This concern was eventually reflected in official policy, with the [Royal Proclamation of 1763](/Royal_Proclamation_of_1763) explicitly prohibiting the sale of alcohol by European settlers to the Indians in Canada, following the British takeover of the territory after their victory over France in the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War) (known in North America as the [French and Indian War](/French_and_Indian_War)).

Following the decisive British takeover of Canada from France, control of the vast [fur trade](/Fur_trade) in North America became, for a time, largely consolidated under the British government. This period of centralized control eventually gave way as the newly formed [United States](/United_States) emerged in the 19th century, also becoming a significant source for furs destined for European markets. Concurrently, the largely unsettled territory of [Russian America](/Russian_America), with its abundant marine and terrestrial wildlife, also developed into a considerable source of furs during this same period. However, the relentless pursuit of fur began to show signs of significant decline starting in the 1830s. This downturn was largely attributed to shifting attitudes and evolving fashions in Europe and America. The once-ubiquitous beaver skin hats, which had fueled the explosive demand for furs and driven the creation and expansion of the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) in the 17th and 18th centuries, fell out of style. While new trends and occasional revivals of prior fashions would cause the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) to experience periods of ebb and flow, its golden age, driven by the beaver hat, was irrevocably over. The fleeting whims of human fashion, it seems, can shape continents more effectively than any monarch.

## Socioeconomic ties

This section does not [cite](/Wikipedia:Citing_sources) any [sources](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Please help [improve this section](/Special:EditPage/Fur_trade) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Unsourced material may be challenged and [removed](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). (June 2016) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

Fur trading at [Fort Nez Percé](/Fort_Nez_Perc%C3%A9) in 1841

Beyond the raw economics of pelts and profits, the political dimensions of the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) frequently eclipsed its purely financial aspects. Trade, in this context, was far more than a simple transaction; it served as a critical instrument for forging alliances and maintaining a semblance of stable relations between vastly different cultures—European and indigenous. The fur traders themselves were often individuals of considerable capital and, by their own societal standards, held a significant social standing. Many younger men, venturing into North America to engage in the [fur trade](/Fur_trade), arrived single. It was common for them to form marriages or cohabit with high-ranking Indian women, partners who held comparable status within their own tribal cultures. This was not merely a matter of convenience; such unions often cemented crucial trade relationships and alliances. In contrast, fur trappers and other laborers, occupying a lower rung on the social ladder, typically formed relationships with lower-ranking indigenous women.

The progeny of these interracial relationships often found themselves occupying a complex, liminal space. Many of their mixed-race descendants, particularly in Canada, developed a distinct cultural identity, now widely recognized as [Métis](/M%C3%A9tis). This emergent culture was deeply rooted in the frontier lifestyle, centered around activities such as fur trapping, hunting, and farming. Paradoxically, these mixed-race individuals often faced exclusion from both Native American and European-American societies. If a Native American tribe operated under a [patrilineal](/Patrilineal) [kinship](/Kinship) system, children born to a white father were typically classified as white, falling under a form of [hypodescent](/Hypodescent)—even if the Native mother and tribe lovingly raised them. Conversely, Europeans, with their own rigid social hierarchies, tended to categorize children born to Native women as Native, regardless of the father's European heritage, mirroring the hypodescent applied to the children of slaves. The Métis community in the Canadian [Red River](/Red_River_of_the_North) region grew so numerous and culturally distinct that they developed their own unique [creole language](/Creole_language) and a vibrant, self-sustaining culture. Significantly, since the late 20th century, the Métis have gained official recognition in Canada as a distinct [First Nations](/First_Nations_in_Canada) ethnic group, a long-overdue acknowledgment of their unique heritage and contributions. Within this mixed-race demographic, a two-tier class structure often emerged: descendants of prominent fur traders and chiefs frequently achieved positions of influence in certain Canadian social, political, and economic circles, while lower-class descendants formed the majority of the distinct [Métis](/M%C3%A9tis) culture, primarily engaged in hunting, trapping, and farming.

Given the immense wealth and strategic advantages at stake, various European-American governments found themselves in fierce competition with diverse native societies for ultimate control over the [fur trade](/Fur_trade). This struggle for dominance was not merely economic; it was deeply political. [Native Americans](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Americas) often made crucial decisions about which side to support in times of conflict based on which European power had consistently provided them with the best trade goods in the most honest and respectful manner. The political significance of trade was so profound that European powers, in a desperate attempt to maintain order and prevent widespread conflict, tried to regulate it. These efforts, however, were often futile. Unscrupulous traders, driven by greed, frequently exploited natives by plying them with alcohol during transactions, a tactic that predictably aroused deep resentment and often escalated into violent confrontations.

A pivotal moment arrived in 1834 when [John Jacob Astor](/John_Jacob_Astor), who had meticulously built the colossal monopoly known as the [American Fur Company](/American_Fur_Company), made the strategic decision to withdraw from the [fur trade](/Fur_trade). Astor, with his keen business acumen, foresaw the inevitable decline: fur-bearing animal populations were dwindling rapidly, and the market itself was undergoing a profound shift, as the once-fashionable beaver hats fell out of style. This decline was further exacerbated by the relentless expansion of European settlement, which systematically displaced native communities from their ancestral and most productive hunting grounds. Concurrently, European demand for furs steadily subsided as fashion trends irrevocably shifted towards other materials. The lifestyles of [Native Americans](/Indigenous_people_of_the_Americas), already profoundly altered by their engagement with the trade, faced further disruption. To continue obtaining the European goods upon which they had grown dependent, and to settle mounting debts, they were often compelled to sell their ancestral lands to European settlers. This resentment, born of forced sales and broken promises, tragically contributed to the outbreak of future wars, a stark reminder of the long-term consequences of economic exploitation.

[Fur Traders Descending the Missouri](/Fur_Traders_Descending_the_Missouri), c. &#8201;1845

Intriguingly, many early exploration parties that ventured into the vast, uncharted territories of North America were, in fact, fur-trading expeditions. These commercial ventures inadvertently became the first recorded instances of Europeans reaching and mapping particular regions of the continent. For example, [Abraham Wood](/Abraham_Wood) dispatched fur-trading parties on extensive exploring expeditions into the rugged southern Appalachian Mountains, inadvertently discovering the [New River](/New_River_(Kanawha_River)) in the process. Similarly, [Simon Fraser](/Simon_Fraser_(explorer)), primarily a fur trader, was instrumental in exploring and charting much of the majestic [Fraser River](/Fraser_River) in British Columbia, leaving an indelible mark on the geographical understanding of the continent. Their pursuit of pelts, it seems, inadvertently expanded the known world.

## Role in economic anthropology

[Economic historians](/Economic_historian) and [anthropologists](/Anthropologist) have long recognized the profound and often complex role the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) played in shaping the early economies of North America. Yet, despite extensive study, they have struggled to agree upon a single, coherent theoretical framework capable of accurately describing the diverse and intricate native economic patterns that characterized this era. It seems even academics struggle with the messy reality of human interaction.

Sketches of life in the [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company) territory, 1875

John C. Phillips and J.W. Smurr, in their influential work, firmly linked the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) to a broader imperial struggle for power. They posited that the trade served a dual purpose: acting both as a potent incentive for territorial expansion and as a crucial method for maintaining dominance over newly acquired regions. In their analysis, the individual experiences, however compelling, were secondary to the grand narrative of global power dynamics, as they sought connections on a global stage that unequivocally revealed the trade's "high political and economic importance." E.E. Rich, however, brought the economic purview down a level, shifting the focus from the macro-level of nation-states to the micro-level of trading companies. He emphasized the pivotal role of these companies and their personnel as the true agents who "opened up" much of Canada's vast territories, rather than attributing this development solely to the actions of the nation-state.

Two Sleighs on a Country Road, Canada, c. &#8201;1835–1848. Image includes a variety of fur throws and clothing, including hides of animals not native to Canada.

Rich's other contributions delve directly into the core of the formalist/substantivist debate, a theoretical schism that dominated, and some might argue, muddied, the field for decades. Historians like [Harold Innis](/Harold_Innis) had long championed the formalist position, particularly within Canadian history, operating under the belief that neoclassical economic principles were universally applicable, influencing non-Western societies in the same fundamental ways they impacted Western ones. However, beginning in the 1950s, substantivists such as [Karl Polanyi](/Karl_Polanyi) mounted a significant challenge to these long-held ideas. Polanyi argued, with considerable force, that primitive societies possessed and utilized alternatives to traditional Western market trade, specifically identifying "gift trade" and "administered trade" as distinct economic systems. Rich, picking up on these compelling arguments in a highly influential article, contended that Indians exhibited "a persistent reluctance to accept European notions or the basic values of the European approach" and, crucially, that "English economic rules did not apply to the Indian trade." He asserted that while Indians were undeniably savvy traders, their fundamental conception of property and economic exchange differed profoundly from that of their European counterparts, a difference that frequently confounded their trading partners. Abraham Rotstein subsequently explicitly integrated these arguments into Polanyi's theoretical framework, asserting that "administered trade was in operation at the Bay and market trade in London," highlighting the coexistence of distinct economic systems within the broader [fur trade](/Fur_trade) context.

Trapper's cabin in [Alaska](/Alaska), 1980s

Arthur J. Ray irrevocably altered the trajectory of economic studies concerning the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) with two highly influential works. He presented a nuanced, modified formalist position that deftly navigated the extremes previously established by Innis and Rotstein. "This trading system," Ray meticulously explained, "is impossible to label neatly as ‘gift trade', or ‘administered trade', or ‘market trade', since it embodies elements of all these forms." This declaration was a crucial acknowledgment of the inherent complexity. Ray argued that Indians engaged in trade for a multiplicity of reasons, suggesting that reducing their motivations to simplistic economic or cultural dichotomies, as both formalists and substantivists had often done, was a fruitless simplification that obscured far more than it revealed. Furthermore, Ray revolutionized the field's methodology by masterfully utilizing previously under-explored trade accounts and account books from the [Hudson's Bay Company's](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company) archives, providing rich qualitative analyses that pushed the boundaries of historical research. Following Ray's insightful lead, Bruce M. White further contributed to a more nuanced understanding, meticulously revealing the complex ways in which native populations integrated new economic relationships into their existing cultural patterns.

Richard White, while conceding that the formalist/substantivist debate had become "old, and now tired"—a sentiment many share about endless academic squabbles—nevertheless attempted to inject new life into the substantivist position. Echoing Ray's moderate stance that cautioned against facile simplifications, White advanced a deceptively simple, yet profound, argument against formalism: "Life was not a business, and such simplifications only distort the past." White argued instead that the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) existed within a complex "middle ground," a space where Europeans and Indians were compelled to accommodate their profound cultural differences. In the specific context of the [fur trade](/Fur_trade), this meant that the French, rather than simply imposing their will, were forced to genuinely learn from the intricate political and cultural meanings with which Indians imbued the fur trade. In this "middle ground," White contended, cooperation, rather than outright domination, frequently prevailed. A refreshing thought, if not always entirely accurate in the long run.

## Present

Despite its diminished historical prominence, the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) is far from extinct, a testament to humanity's enduring, if sometimes questionable, desires. According to the [Fur Institute of Canada](/Fur_Institute_of_Canada), there are still approximately 60,000 active trappers across [Canada](/Canada), a figure based on official trapping licenses. Of these, a significant proportion, around 25,000, are identified as [indigenous peoples](/Indigenous_people), highlighting the continued cultural and economic ties within these communities. The fur farming industry also maintains a presence in various regions of Canada, a more controlled, industrialized approach to pelt production.

[Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia) stands out as the largest producer of mink and foxes within Canada, a surprising agricultural powerhouse. In 2012 alone, the province's fur farms generated revenues nearing $150&#160;million, accounting for a substantial one-quarter of all agricultural production in Nova Scotia. In the [United States](/United_States), the industry also persists, albeit on a smaller scale. In 2000, there were 351 mink farms operating, contributing to the supply chain. As of 2015, the nation counted 176,573 trappers, with the majority concentrated in the midwestern states, where trapping traditions remain stronger. However, a notable shift occurred in 2015 when California became the first, and currently only, state to implement a ban on trapping for both commercial and recreational purposes, signaling a growing legislative response to animal welfare concerns.

The North American Fur Auction (NAFA) continues to operate, holding sales four times a year and attracting a diverse array of buyers from around the world, underscoring the international demand that still exists for natural fur. Furthermore, the Northeast Association of Fish & Wildlife Agencies reports that, at present, approximately 270,000 families across the [United States](/United_States) and Canada derive at least some portion of their income from fur trapping. So, while the grand narratives of empire-building have faded, the quiet, persistent hum of the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) continues, a small, often controversial, thread in the fabric of modern economies.

## Maritime fur trade

*Main article: [Maritime fur trade](/Maritime_fur_trade)*

The North West Coast during the [maritime fur trade](/Maritime_fur_trade) era, about 1790 to 1840

The [maritime fur trade](/Maritime_fur_trade) represented a distinct, ship-based system of commerce, a sprawling network that focused on the acquisition of furs, predominantly those of [sea otters](/Sea_otter) and other marine mammals, from the skilled [indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest Coast](/Indigenous_peoples_of_the_Pacific_Northwest_Coast) and the [natives of Alaska](/Alaska_Natives). These highly sought-after furs were then primarily transported across the vast Pacific and traded in the bustling markets of China. There, they were exchanged for an array of coveted Chinese goods—exquisite teas, luxurious silks, delicate porcelain, and other exotic commodities—which were subsequently sold for substantial profits in Europe and the [United States](/United_States). It was a truly globalized supply chain long before the term existed.

The Russians, driven by their relentless eastward expansion, pioneered this maritime trade, steadily working their way from [Kamchatka](/Kamchatka) along the chain of the [Aleutian Islands](/Aleutian_Islands) to the southern coast of Alaska. British and American traders, ever alert to new opportunities, entered the fray during the 1780s, initially focusing their efforts on what is now the [coast of British Columbia](/British_Columbia_Coast). The trade experienced a dramatic boom around the turn of the 19th century, a period of intense activity and immense profits. However, a prolonged period of decline began in the 1810s, largely precipitated by the relentless hunting that severely depleted the once-abundant sea otter population. As the prime commodity became scarce, the [maritime fur trade](/Maritime_fur_trade) demonstrated a remarkable adaptability, diversifying its offerings and tapping into new markets and commodities, all while maintaining its core focus on the Northwest Coast and China. This complex system persisted until the middle to late 19th century. Throughout this entire era, Russians maintained an undeniable dominance over most of the coast of what is now Alaska. South of Alaska, however, the waters were a battleground of fierce competition between, and among, British and American trading vessels, each vying for supremacy. The British were the first to establish operations in this southern sector, but they ultimately proved unable to compete effectively against the aggressive and well-capitalized Americans, who dominated the trade from the 1790s to the 1830s. In a strategic counter-move, the British [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company) entered the coastal trade in the 1820s with the explicit intention of driving out its American rivals, a goal it largely accomplished by approximately 1840. In its twilight years, the [maritime fur trade](/Maritime_fur_trade) was predominantly conducted by the formidable British [Hudson's Bay Company](/Hudson%27s_Bay_Company) and the equally powerful [Russian-American Company](/Russian-American_Company).

The Russian fur traders, extending their reach from Alaska, established their largest and most southerly settlement in California, [Fort Ross](/Fort_Ross,_California), in 1812, a testament to the global ambition fueled by fur. The term "maritime fur trade" itself was coined by historians, a convenient label used to distinguish this coastal, ship-based system from the continental, land-based [fur trade](/Fur_trade) exemplified by companies like the [North West Company](/North_West_Company) and the [American Fur Company](/American_Fur_Company). Historically, this particular branch of the trade was not known by this modern designation; rather, it was commonly referred to as the "North West Coast trade" or simply "North West Trade." Interestingly, the term "North West" was rarely spelled as the single word "Northwest," as is customary today, a small linguistic ghost of a bygone era.

The [maritime fur trade](/Maritime_fur_trade) acted as a powerful conduit, drawing the [Pacific Northwest](/Pacific_Northwest) coast into an expansive, unprecedented [international trade](/International_trade) network. This network, centered on the vast north Pacific Ocean, was truly global in its scope, fundamentally driven by the principles of [capitalism](/Capitalism) but, for the most part, not by direct [colonialism](/Colonialism) in the traditional sense. A complex [triangular trade](/Triangular_trade) network rapidly emerged, intricately linking the Pacific Northwest coast, the markets of China, the recently "discovered" (by the [Western world](/Western_world)) [Hawaiian Islands](/Hawaiian_Islands), the mercantile centers of Europe, and the nascent industries of the [United States](/United_States), particularly [New England](/New_England).

This trade had a profound and often devastating impact on the indigenous peoples of the Pacific Northwest coast, most notably the [Aleut](/Aleut_people), [Tlingit](/Tlingit_people), [Haida](/Haida_people), [Nuu-chah-nulth](/Nuu-chah-nulth_people), and [Chinook peoples](/Chinook_people). While it brought a rapid increase in material wealth, it also ushered in an era of heightened warfare, intensified [potlatching](/Potlatch) (competitive ceremonial feasts), increased slaving, and, most tragically, severe depopulation due to successive [epidemic](/Epidemic) diseases against which native populations had no immunity. Concurrently, it led to an enhanced importance of [totems](/Totem) and traditional nobility crests, as wealth was often invested in these cultural markers. Despite these profound disruptions, the indigenous culture was not simply overwhelmed; rather, it underwent a dynamic period of flourishing and rapid transformation. The emergence and widespread use of [Chinook Jargon](/Chinook_Jargon), a pidgin trade language, arose directly from this maritime fur trading era and remains a distinctive and enduring aspect of Pacific Northwest culture. [Native Hawaiian](/Native_Hawaiian) society was similarly affected by the sudden influx of Western wealth and technology, alongside the devastating toll of epidemic diseases. The trade's direct effect on distant China and Europe, however, was comparatively minimal, serving more as a conduit for goods than a force for societal restructuring.

For [New England](/New_England), however, the [maritime fur trade](/Maritime_fur_trade) and the significant profits it generated played a crucial role in revitalizing the region, contributing directly to its transformation from an agrarian society to an industrial powerhouse. The substantial wealth generated by the [fur trade](/Fur_trade) was strategically reinvested into industrial development, most notably fueling the burgeoning [textile manufacturing](/Textile_manufacturing) sector. This burgeoning New England textile industry, in a cruel twist of fate, in turn had a massive and devastating effect on [slavery in the United States](/Slavery_in_the_United_States), drastically increasing the demand for raw cotton. This escalating demand directly facilitated the rapid expansion of the cotton [plantation system](/Plantation_system) across the entire [Deep South](/Deep_South), demonstrating the unforeseen and tragic interconnectedness of global commerce.

A sea otter, drawing by S. Smith after [John Webber](/John_Webber)
Modern and historical ranges of [sea otter](/Sea_otter) subspecies

The most lucrative furs, the true "soft gold" of the maritime trade, were those of [sea otters](/Sea_otter), with the northern sea otter, *Enhydra lutris kenyoni*, inhabiting the coastal waters between the [Columbia River](/Columbia_River) to the south and [Cook Inlet](/Cook_Inlet) to the north, being particularly prized. The fur of the Californian southern sea otter, *E.&#160;l.&#160;nereis*, while still valuable, was considered less luxurious and consequently less profitable. The relentless, unsustainable hunting of the northern sea otter ultimately led to its [local extinction](/Local_extinction) in many areas, prompting maritime fur traders to shift their operations southward to California. There, the southern sea otter suffered a similar fate, also being hunted to the brink of extinction. A pattern of exploitation, it seems, is rarely broken until the resource itself is gone.

Furs acquired by British and American maritime traders were primarily transported to the Chinese port of [Guangzhou](/Guangzhou) (known historically as Canton), where they operated within the established and highly regulated [Canton System](/Canton_System). Furs originating from [Russian America](/Russian_America), on the other hand, were largely sold to China via the Mongolian trading town of [Kyakhta](/Kyakhta), a crucial overland hub that had been opened to Russian trade by the 1727 [Treaty of Kyakhta](/Treaty_of_Kyakhta). The routes changed, but the destination for luxury remained the same.

